{
  "answer": "Surah Ta-Ha 20:114 establishes the continuous pursuit of learning by commanding the Prophet Muhammad to pray, \"My Lord, increase me in knowledge\" [1]. \n\nSurah Al-Baqarah 2:260 demonstrates that questioning to achieve absolute certainty is a valid practice, as Abraham asks God how He brings the dead to life specifically so his heart may be satisfied and stronger in faith [2, 3]. \n\nSurah S\u0101d 38:29 anchors the practice of interrogating scripture by stating the Quran was revealed so that people of understanding might deeply reflect upon its verses [4]. \n\nSurah An-Nisa 4:82 emphasizes active analysis by challenging readers to reflect upon the Quran, noting that if it were not from God, they would find much contradiction within it [5]. \n\nSurah Az-Zumar 39:18 praises active evaluation, describing guided people of understanding as those who carefully listen to speech and follow the best of it [6].",
  "conversation_id": "b75c54d4-0ca8-4686-8f68-eef116d359e6",
  "turn_number": 1,
  "is_follow_up": true,
